---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base title="Why I Forked Sympozium for 100% Google Cloud">

<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-inner">

    <header>
      <a href="/blog" class="back">← Back to Build Log</a>
      <time>March 15, 2026</time>
      <h1>Why I Forked Sympozium for 100% Google Cloud</h1>
      <p class="lead">The original platform supports OpenAI, Anthropic, Azure, and Ollama. I stripped it all out and rebuilt for GKE + Gemini. Here's why a single-cloud bet makes sense for Kubernetes-native AI.</p>
    </header>

    <section>
      <h2>The Starting Point</h2>
      <p>
        Sympozium is an open-source, Kubernetes-native AI agent orchestration platform created by
        Alex Jones. It's genuinely impressive — CRDs for agent personas, skill sidecars, policy
        admission controllers, and an event bus for inter-agent communication. The architecture
        is sound.
      </p>
      <p>
        But the original supports <em>everything</em>: OpenAI, Anthropic, Azure OpenAI, Ollama,
        plus Slack, Telegram, WhatsApp, and Discord as channels, NATS JetStream as the event bus,
        GitHub Actions for CI/CD, and GHCR for container images. That breadth is a feature for
        the open-source community. For a GCP-focused deployment, it's complexity.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Thesis: Single-Cloud Coherence</h2>
      <p>
        Multi-cloud AI platforms pay a tax at every integration point. Each LLM provider has a
        different API shape, different auth model, different rate limiting behavior, and different
        pricing structure. The abstraction layer that normalizes them is never free — it's code
        you maintain, edge cases you handle, and capabilities you can't access because they don't
        exist across all providers.
      </p>
      <p>
        By going 100% Google Cloud, I removed that abstraction layer entirely. The platform speaks
        Vertex AI natively. Auth is Workload Identity — no API keys, no JSON credentials, no
        secret rotation. The event bus is Cloud Pub/Sub — no NATS cluster to operate. Credentials
        live in Secret Manager — no Kubernetes Secrets base64 encoding. Every component
        authenticates to every other component through GKE's identity plane.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What Got Replaced</h2>
      <p>
        Here's the full mapping. Every non-Google service was replaced with a GCP-native equivalent:
      </p>

      <div class="replacement-table">
        <div class="rep-row rep-header">
          <span>Before</span>
          <span>After</span>
          <span>Why</span>
        </div>
        <div class="rep-row">
          <span>OpenAI / Anthropic / Azure</span>
          <span>Vertex AI Gemini</span>
          <span>Three model tiers (Flash, Pro, Preview) with function calling</span>
        </div>
        <div class="rep-row">
          <span>Ollama</span>
          <span>Gemma 3 on vLLM/TGI</span>
          <span>Self-hosted on GKE GPU (L4, A100) and TPU v5e nodes</span>
        </div>
        <div class="rep-row">
          <span>NATS JetStream</span>
          <span>Cloud Pub/Sub</span>
          <span>Managed, no cluster to operate, trace context propagation</span>
        </div>
        <div class="rep-row">
          <span>Slack / Telegram / WhatsApp</span>
          <span>Google Chat</span>
          <span>Cards v2, slash commands, native Workspace integration</span>
        </div>
        <div class="rep-row">
          <span>K8s Secrets</span>
          <span>Secret Manager</span>
          <span>Versioning, audit logging, IAM-based access control</span>
        </div>
        <div class="rep-row">
          <span>ConfigMap memory</span>
          <span>Firestore</span>
          <span>No 1MB limit, structured documents, optimistic concurrency</span>
        </div>
        <div class="rep-row">
          <span>GitHub Actions + GHCR</span>
          <span>Cloud Build + Artifact Registry</span>
          <span>Same-VPC builds, Workload Identity, vulnerability scanning</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Model Tier System</h2>
      <p>
        One of the biggest design decisions was the model tier system. Instead of "pick a model
        name string," every agent persona maps to a tier:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fast</strong> (gemini-2.5-flash) — monitoring, log tailing, status checks</li>
        <li><strong>Balanced</strong> (gemini-2.5-pro) — the default, code review, incident response</li>
        <li><strong>Powerful</strong> (gemini-3.1-pro-preview) — security audits, complex planning</li>
        <li><strong>Local</strong> (gemma-3-27b-it) — self-hosted, air-gapped, cost-sensitive</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The SRE persona gets "fast" because it needs quick responses during incidents. The
        security auditor gets "powerful" because it needs deep reasoning. The default for
        everything is Pro — not Flash. This was a deliberate choice: optimize for quality first,
        then use tiers to control cost where it matters.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Hybrid Inference</h2>
      <p>
        The most interesting architecture decision is hybrid inference. A <code>node-probe</code>
        DaemonSet runs on every GPU and TPU node in the GKE cluster. It checks for vLLM, TGI,
        and TPU inference servers at known ports, discovers which Gemma models are loaded, and
        annotates the node.
      </p>
      <p>
        The controller then has a live map of what models are available where. An agent run can
        be routed to Vertex AI Gemini for cloud inference or to a specific GKE node running
        Gemma locally — all transparent to the persona definition.
      </p>
      <p>
        For TPU nodes specifically, the probe detects GKE-specific node labels
        (<code>cloud.google.com/gke-tpu-topology</code>,
        <code>cloud.google.com/gke-tpu-accelerator</code>) and sets a
        <code>sympozium.ai/inference-accelerator: tpu</code> annotation. The Helm chart includes
        TPU tolerations so the probe runs on TPU-only node pools.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What's Next</h2>
      <p>
        Three features are on the roadmap that push this further into GCP-native territory:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>GKE Inference Gateway</strong> — model-aware routing with KV-cache-aware load balancing for self-hosted models</li>
        <li><strong>GKE Agent Sandbox</strong> — gVisor isolation for agent pods with sub-second warm pool startup</li>
        <li><strong>Kubecost integration</strong> — per-agent, per-model cost attribution using Kubernetes labels</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The goal is a platform where every Kubernetes concept — Pods, Jobs, DaemonSets, CRDs,
        admission webhooks — maps to an AI agent concept, and every GCP service is used for
        what it does best. Not a wrapper around APIs, but a native platform.
      </p>
    </section>

  </div>
</article>

<style>
  .blog-post { padding: 60px 24px 80px; }
  .post-inner { max-width: 700px; margin: 0 auto; }
  .back { font-size: 13px; color: var(--gcp-blue); text-decoration: none; display: block; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  .back:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
  header time { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-muted); }
  header h1 { font-size: 40px; font-weight: 800; line-height: 1.15; letter-spacing: -0.5px; margin-top: 8px; }
  .lead { font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--text-muted); margin-top: 16px; }

  section { margin-top: 40px; }
  section h2 { font-size: 24px; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  section p { font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 16px; }
  section ul { list-style: none; padding: 0; }
  section li { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--text-muted); padding: 6px 0 6px 20px; position: relative; }
  section li::before { content: '→'; position: absolute; left: 0; color: var(--gcp-blue); }
  section li strong { color: var(--text); }
  section code { font-size: 14px; background: var(--surface-3); padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; }
  section em { color: var(--text); font-style: italic; }

  .replacement-table { margin-top: 16px; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; overflow: hidden; }
  .rep-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1.5fr; gap: 12px; padding: 12px 16px; font-size: 13px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .rep-row:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .rep-header { background: var(--surface-3); font-weight: 700; font-size: 12px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px; color: var(--text-muted); }
  .rep-row span:first-child { color: var(--text-muted); text-decoration: line-through; }
  .rep-row:not(.rep-header) span:first-child { opacity: 0.7; }
  .rep-row span:nth-child(2) { color: var(--gcp-green); font-weight: 600; }
  .rep-row span:nth-child(3) { color: var(--text-muted); }
</style>

</Base>
